Presently Junior HRD Minister in the UPA Government, Purandreshwari is the daughter of TDP founder N T Rama Rao. She, along with husband Daggubati Venkateshwara Rao, joined the Congress in 2004. She is the first women in NTRs family to enter electoral politics. She won from the Bapatla Lok Sabha seat in 2004 and was made a Union Minister of State for HRD in January 2006. Due to delimitation of seats, she shifted to Visakhapatnam seat in the 2009 Lok Sabha elections. A double graduate in literature and gemology, she authored a book In quest of Utopia. Highly respected among political circles, she is said to be close to Sonia and Rahul Gandhi, and an arch rival to TDP chief N Chandrababu Naidu, who was responsible for dethroning her father and then sidelining her husband.

His father Murasoli Maran was former union industries and commerce minister. After Murasoli Maran's death, Dayanidhi entered into politics. As a debutant MP he became India's youngest IT minister in 2004. He is also the grand nephew of chief minister and DMK president M Karunanidhi. The young Maran was asked to step down from the post of union minister by the party leadership following a bitter family dispute. He was given ticket again following his rapprochement with Karunanidhi family.

Deepa is the wife of ailing Congress leader and former union minister Priyaranjan Dasmunshi. She is a former actress. Deepa is a known critic of Trinamool and this factor has said to have prevented her from joining the Manmohan Singh government as a junior minister.

An army major, Jaswant is among few non RSS leaders who reached to the top in the BJP. He became a party member, soon after BJP was founded and was elected to Rajya Sabha in 1980. In fact, during the BJP-led NDA rule, Jaswant held defence, external affairs and finance portfolios before falling out the parent organisaton over favourable portrayal of Mohammad Ali Jinnah, founder of Pakistan in his book on the partition of the Indian subcontinent in 1947. He enjoys clean image. Jaswant's son Manvendra is a journalist turned politician.

KCR as he is popularly known is perhaps, the most feared politician in Andhra Pradesh. He has never lost an election since 1985. He was a member of State Assembly (1985-2004) and was elected to Lok Sabha in 2004 and 2009  and in two by-elections from Karimnagar seat between 2004-2009, both forced because of his resignations in protest over Telangana. Unlike other politicians, his political journey has been controversial and rough. He is known for his arrogant belief in his ability to get elected, and frequently threatens to resign. He resigned from Deputy Speaker post, as MLA and from TDP to float his own party Telangana Rashtra Samithi (TRS). He resigned from Lok Sabha seat twice and got re-elected, and also resigned as a Union Minister. With limited political power, he forced the UPA government to accede Statehood for Telangana although the government later changed its decision due to political turmoil with his famous hunger strike till death call.

Daughter of freedom fighter late Promileswar Banerjee, Mamata forayed into politics when she joined West Bengal Chhatra Parishad, student wing of Congress, while studying at the Jogmaya Debi College in Kolkata in 1970s. Graduating to party politics, she was General Secretary of West Bengal Mahila Congress in 1979-80 and subsequently held other posts in Congress. In 1984, she contested the Lok Sabha elections on a Congress ticket from Jadavpur and won against veteran Left leader Somnath Chatterjee.

Raghuvansh is a 'thinker' in Laloo's RJD. He has earned a reputaton as a politician with integrity and efficiency. A socialist to the core, Raghuvansh is a product of JP movement. He had his baptism in politics when he took active part in political agitations and underwent imprisonment. Having won the Lok Sabha elections from Vaishali in Bihar for the fifth time in a row, Raghuvansh has done his MSc and PhD and was a lecturer in Mathematics in Goenka College, Sitamarhi, under Bihar University. He was dismissed from the University service during Emergency and was reinstated later.

He is a rare breed of senior Congress leaders with a clean and non-controversial image owing to his integrity and professional qualifications. He got elected to the state Assembly for four consecutive terms from 1969 to 1984. In 1984, he got elected to the Lok Sabha for the first time. Twice, he was a member of the Rajya Sabha (1990-96 and 1997-98). He quit his Rajya Sabha seat after he got re-elected to Lok Sabha in the1998 elections and has retained the seat for last 12 years. However, due to de-limitation of seats, he had to change his constituency from Mahabubnagar to Chevella. He became Union Minister (Information & Broadcasting) for first time in 1997-98 and was again inducted as a minister after UPA came to power in 2004. Renowned for his work on the Prasar Bharti broadcasting bill, which became a basis for the State-run Indian television Doordarshans media autonomy.

A popular tribal leader, Soren went on to become a founding member of the Jharkhand Mukti Morcha which succesfully campaigned for a separate Jharkhand state. His reputation as a corrupt politician who is directly invovled in criminal cases has had no bearing on his fluctuating political fortunes. Soren was a Union Minister and a Chief Minister and spent time in jail. To his supporters, he is known as Dishom Guru or  great leader. Soren was accused of taking money to support Narasimha Rao on the eve of a crucial trust vote. He was given a sum of approximately Rs 30 lakhs to ensure that Rao remained PM. He took the money from the Congress managers and went straight to the Punjab National Bank where he opened an account and deposited the money. He invested in property too, but again in his own name. His failure to cover up the money trail led to the accusations in the Narasimha Rao incident.
